Subject: using string from apr_pstrdup results in httpd segfault, error 4 in libc.so.6 - I was doing something wrong... (solved, sharing for others)
Mime-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=utf-8
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 8bit
X-Source-Archive: Apache httpd dev public mailing list apache_httpd_dev_2023-11.mbox

While I was preparing my questions in the below email (rebooting resulted in error 5 too) - I found my own answer.

I found out that I was missing an include at the top of the file when I saw:

mod_certs.c:81:22: warning: assignment to 'char *' from 'int' makes pointer from integer without a cast [-Wint-conversion]
   81 |         config->name = apr_pstrdup(parms->pool, v);

Which made no sense, then I remembered that C defaults to return type of int, if it does not know the declaration. So I looked harder and found:

mod_certs.c:43:16: warning: implicit declaration of function 'apr_pstrdup' [-Wimplicit-function-declaration]
   43 |     char* test=apr_pstrdup(parms->pool, arg);
      |                ^~~~~~~~~~~

Which was fixed by:

#include "apr_strings.h"


Going forward, I have -Wc,-Werror=implicit-function-declaration on apxs


-Jason


